04152nam a22006375i 9780520323629DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805203236297 a10.1525/97805203236292doi  a(DE-B1597)569295  a(OCoLC)1198929546  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aLIT0041202bisacsh04a809/.933551 aRoss, Charles, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Custom of the Castle :bFrom Malory to Macbeth /cCharles Ross.  aPortions of this book have been published in earlier versions, Reprint 2020 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (224 p.) :b1 frontisp.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAbbreviations -- tPreface -- t1. THE FRENCH MODEL -- t1. Introduction -- t2. Malory's Weeping Castle -- tII. THE ITALIAN TRANSITION -- t3. Boiardo's Castle Cruel -- t4. Ariosto's Fable of Power -- tIII. THE ENGLISH CONCLUSION -- t5. Spenser's Customs of Courtesy -- t6. Hamlet's Ghost Fear -- t7. Macbeth's Future: "A Thing of Custom" -- t8. Epilogue: The Disappearing Castle -- tAppendix 1 -- tAppendix 2 -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe "custom of the castle" imposes strange ordeals on knights and ladies seeking hospitality--daunting, mostly evil challenges that travelers must obey or even defend. This seemingly fantastic motif, first conceived by Chrètien de Troyes in the twelfth century and widely imitated in medieval French romance, flowered again when Italian and English authors adopted it during the century before Shakespeare's plays and the rise of the novel. Unlike other scholars who have dismissed it as pure literary convention, Charles Ross finds serious social purpose behind the custom of the castle. Ross explores the changing legal and cultural conceptions of custom in France, Italy, and England to uncover a broad array of moral issues in the many castle stories. He concentrates on single scenes that are common to a series of epics, showing how their nuanced narratives reflect real social limits of order, violence, justice, civility, and political conformity. His investigation of masterpieces from the thirteenth-century Lancelot to The Faerie Queene--by way of Malory, Boiardo, and Ariosto--demonstrates for the first time the impact on Shakespeare's plays, particularly Macbeth, of an earlier way of thinking about the strengths and weaknesses of social customs.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aEnglish literature. 4aMacbeth. 4aMiddle Ages. 4aShakespeare. 4aWilliam Shakespeare. 4aliterary motives. 4aliterary topics. 4aliterature. 4amotives. 4atopics. 4aviolence. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052032361240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520323629?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520323629423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520323629/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles